Here's a practical approach:

## 1. Define each theme as a `ResourceDictionary`

```xml
<!-- Resources/Themes/LightTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
                    xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml">
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#1A1A1A</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#0078D4</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Resources/Themes/DarkTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...>
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#1E1E1E</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#E0E0E0</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#4FC3F7</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

```xml
<!-- Resources/Themes/HighContrastTheme.xaml -->
<ResourceDictionary ...>
    <Color x:Key="PageBackground">#000000</Color>
    <Color x:Key="TextPrimary">#FFFFFF</Color>
    <Color x:Key="AccentColor">#FFFF00</Color>
</ResourceDictionary>
```

## 2. Create a theme service

```csharp
public enum AppTheme { Light, Dark, HighContrast }

public static class ThemeService
{
    public static void ApplyTheme(AppTheme theme)
    {
        var mergedDicts = Application.Current!.Resources.MergedDictionaries;

        // Remove any existing theme dictionary (keep other merged resources)
        var existing = mergedDicts.FirstOrDefault(d => d is IThemeDictionary);
        if (existing is not null)
            mergedDicts.Remove(existing);

        ResourceDictionary newTheme = theme switch
        {
            AppTheme.Dark         => new Resources.Themes.DarkTheme(),
            AppTheme.HighContrast => new Resources.Themes.HighContrastTheme(),
            _                     => new Resources.Themes.LightTheme(),
        };

        mergedDicts.Add(newTheme);

        // Persist the choice
        Preferences.Set("app_theme", theme.ToString());
    }

    public static AppTheme LoadSavedTheme()
    {
        var saved = Preferences.Get("app_theme", nameof(AppTheme.Light));
        return Enum.TryParse<AppTheme>(saved, out var t) ? t : AppTheme.Light;
    }
}
```

> **Tip:** If you want the `FirstOrDefault` filter, tag each theme XAML class with a marker interface (`IThemeDictionary`). Otherwise, just always keep the theme as the **last** dictionary and replace by index.

## 3. Apply on startup

In `App.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
public App()
{
    InitializeComponent();
    ThemeService.ApplyTheme(ThemeService.LoadSavedTheme());
}
```

## 4. Settings page picker

```xml
<Picker x:Name="ThemePicker"
        Title="Theme"
        SelectedIndexChanged="OnThemeChanged">
    <Picker.ItemsSource>
        <x:Array Type="{x:Type x:String}">
            <x:String>Light</x:String>
            <x:String>Dark</x:String>
            <x:String>HighContrast</x:String>
        </x:Array>
    </Picker.ItemsSource>
</Picker>
```

```csharp
void OnThemeChanged(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    if (ThemePicker.SelectedItem is string name &&
        Enum.TryParse<AppTheme>(name, out var theme))
    {
        ThemeService.ApplyTheme(theme);
    }
}
```

## 5. Consume theme colors in any page

Use `DynamicResource` (not `StaticResource`) so values update live when the dictionary swaps:

```xml
<ContentPage BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource PageBackground}">
    <Label Text="Hello" TextColor="{DynamicResource TextPrimary}" />
    <Button BackgroundColor="{DynamicResource AccentColor}" Text="Go" />
</ContentPage>
```

**Key points:**
- **`DynamicResource`** is essential — it re-evaluates when the dictionary changes at runtime.
- **`Preferences`** persists the choice across launches.
- Keep the same `x:Key` names in every theme dictionary so the swap is seamless.
